    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Orthodox Viewpoints: Can They All Be Right?</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Phyllis Behrens Pritcher letter on August 20 article on Long Island's Orthodox Jews recalls being ridiculed as child (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>Growing up in the 30's in Woodmere, I remember hearing ''dirty Jew'' called out as I walked through the village, and riding the school bus, I learned that Jews were in the minority and not wanted.</p>
        <p>From attending my first High Holy Day services, held in the firehouse (there was no synagogue in Woodmere or Hewlett then) to my graduation from Woodmere High School, I experienced the assimilation of the Jews in the Five Towns.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>Growing up in the 30's in Woodmere, I remember hearing ''dirty Jew'' called out as I walked through the village, and riding the school bus, I learned that Jews were in the minority and not wanted.</p>
        <p>From attending my first High Holy Day services, held in the firehouse (there was no synagogue in Woodmere or Hewlett then) to my graduation from Woodmere High School, I experienced the assimilation of the Jews in the Five Towns.</p>
        <p>I was disturbed to read we now sit in judgment on ourselves, on how we wish to observe our religion. Some things never change. Some people are never satisfied.</p>
        <p>PHYLLIS BEHRENS PRITCHER  Boca Raton, Fla.</p>
      </block>
